{{notability|Neologisms|date=May 2015}} {{ref improve|date=May 2015}} '''Pluriculturalism''' is an approach to the self and others as complex rich beings which act and react from the perspective of multiple identifications. In this case, identity or identities are the by-products of experiences in different cultures. As an effect, multiple identifications create a unique personality instead of or more than a static identity.<ref name=Scribd>[https://www.scribd.com/doc/48131676/pluriculturalism-2 pluriculturalism (2)]</ref> It is based on multiple-identity, wherein people have multiple identities who belong to multiple groups with different degrees of identification.<ref name=UGR>Trujillo Sáez, Fernando. [http://www.ugr.es/~ftsaez/aspectos/LEA.pdf Culture Awareness and the development of the pluricultural competence], page 3</ref> The term '''pluricultural competence''' is a consequence of the idea of [[plurilingualism]].<ref name=COE>[http://www.coe.int/t/dg4/linguistic/Source/SourcePublications/CompetencePlurilingue09web_en.pdf 5.1. The concept of pluricultural competence], 5. PLURICULTURAL COMPETENCE: DESCRIPTIVE PRINCIPLES, coe.int</ref> There is a distinction between pluriculturalism and [[multiculturalism]].<ref name=COE />
[[Spain]] has been referred to as a pluricultural country, due to its [[Nationalisms and regionalisms of Spain|nationalisms and regionalisms]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Spain’s general election|url=https://www.economist.com/news/leaders/21684152-new-liberal-party-offers-antidote-populist-euro-blues-feliz-navidad-espa|accessdate=21 December 2015|work=[[The Economist]]|date=19 December 2015}}</ref>
