'''Resignation syndrome''' (in Swedish ''Uppgivenhetssyndrom'') is a dissociative syndrome that induces a catatonic state. This disorder mainly affects young people who have suffered psychological trauma<ref>« Resignation Syndrome: Catatonia? Culture-Bound? », Frontiers in Behavioral Neuroscience, 2016, vol. 10, no 7, doi: 10.3389/fnbeh.2016.00007</ref>. Depicted as a [[culture-bound syndrome]], it has chiefly been observed in Sweden among children of asylum seekers from former Soviet and Yugoslav countries<ref>Aviv, Rachel, « The Trauma of Facing Deportation », The New Yorker, April 3, 2017 <https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2017/04/03/the-trauma-of-facing-deportation>.</ref>. It has also recently been observed in refugee children on Nauru, an Australian immigration detention center<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-08-16/12-year-old-refugee-with-resignation-syndrome-on-nauru/10129408 |title=12yo refugee on hunger strike on Nauru suffering from resignation syndrome, doctors say - ABC News (Australian Broadcasting Corporation) |publisher=Abc.net.au |date=2018-08-16 |accessdate=2018-09-25}}</ref>.
