{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2016}}
{{Use British English|date=April 2016}}

'''William Burdett-Coutts''' is the founder and director of theatre and comedy promotion company [[Assembly (events promoter)|Assembly]], one of the major venue operators at the [[Edinburgh Festival Fringe]], the world's largest arts festival.<ref name=BBC120502/>

He was born in [[Zimbabwe]], and began his career as a theatre director in Scotland in the late 1970s, before establishing the [[Assembly Rooms, Edinburgh|Assembly Rooms]] as a [[fringe theatre]] venue in 1981, leasing it from [[Edinburgh Council]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2507&dat=19810717&id=XO5AAAAAIBAJ&sjid=kacMAAAAIBAJ&pg=2563,3217771&hl=en|title=The Glasgow Herald - Google News Archive Search|publisher=}}</ref> 
The venue has been referred to as the "National Theatre of the Fringe".<ref name=WOS/>

Burdett-Coutts came to operate the venue after he was too late to find anywhere else to stage the play he intended to bring to the Fringe, [[The Madman and the Nun]]. He was working at the [[Old Vic]] at the time. The Assembly Rooms on [[George Street, Edinburgh|George Street]] had previously been home to the Festival Club, but they had vacated the building after finding it unprofitable to operate. This left it available for Burdett-Coutts, and gave him space to host other shows.<ref name=Venables170606/>

Burdett-Coutts fought for the Assembly Rooms to remain a venue only building, against Edinburgh Council's plan to turn the ground floor space into shops and a restaurant.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edinburghnews.scotsman.com/news/william-burdett-coutts-don-t-bring-curtain-down-on-assembly-as-we-know-it-1-1313744|title=William Burdett-Coutts: Don't bring curtain down on Assembly as we know it|publisher=}}</ref>

